class Solution:
    def minimizedStringLength(self, s: str) -> int:
        stack = []
        for c in s:
            if stack and stack[-1] == c:
                stack.pop()
            else:
                stack.append(c)
        return len(stack)
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a stack to keep track of the characters in the string. It iterates over the string, and for each character, it checks if the top of the stack is the same character. If it is, it pops the character from the stack, effectively removing the closest occurrence of the character to the left. If it's not, it pushes the character onto the stack. At the end, the length of the stack is the length of the minimized string. This solution has a high efficiency because it only requires a single pass over the string and uses a stack to keep track of the characters.

